<subSubSection id="4FFC65060B6B165A78E8FF5C2793FE8D" pageId="27" pageNumber="132" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="0759368D0B6B165A78E8FF5C2793FE8D" blockId="27.[136,1452,158,724]" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B6B165A78E8FF5C26D5FF11" bold="true" box="[189,399,158,184]" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
—The species belongs to section 
<taxonomicName id="C0E64D0E0B6B165A7B51FF5C2418FF11" box="[772,834,158,184]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="27" pageNumber="132" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Sidae">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B6B165A7B51FF5C2418FF11" box="[772,834,158,184]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">Sidae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<tableCitation id="4A6403360B6B165A7B04FF5C24F9FF11" box="[849,931,158,184]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,224,340,364]" captionTargetBox="[144,1440,425,1289]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Sections of Sida with species occurring in Rio Grande do Sul state, and their diagnostic features, according to Fryxell (1985) and Krapovickas (2003)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/539966050B72164378DDFE962568FE39" pageId="27" pageNumber="132" tableUuid="539966050B72164378DDFE962568FE39">Table 1</tableCitation>
) Series 
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B6B165A7C55FF5D2336FF11" box="[1024,1132,159,184]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">Viarumae</emphasis>
. This Series is characterized by the presence of 5 mericarps (
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6B165A79A0FF002590FF75" author="Krapovickas, A." box="[501,714,194,220]" pageId="27" pageNumber="132" pagination="65 - 118" refId="ref19583" refString="Krapovickas, A. (2014) Nuevas especies de Sida Seccion Sida (Malvaceae). Bonplandia 23: 65 - 118. https: // doi. org / 10.30972 / bon. 232258" type="journal article" year="2014">Krapovickas 2014</bibRefCitation>
). The species is also characterized by the persistent stipules after leaf fall, by calyx 
<quantity id="C01E9B680B6B165A7909FF2426C5FEA8" box="[348,415,230,257]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="132" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
long (
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6B165A79BFFF242581FEA9" author="Monteiro-Filho, H. da" box="[490,731,230,256]" pageId="27" pageNumber="132" pagination="501 - 522" refId="ref20015" refString="Monteiro-Filho, H. da C. (1949) As especies argentinas, brasileiras e uruguayas da seccao Malvinda do genero Sida (Malvaceas). Lilloa 17: 501 - 522." type="journal article" year="1949">Monteiro-Filho 1949</bibRefCitation>
) and corolla white with adaxial red basal spot (
<figureCitation id="9FDD2A080B6B165A7D54FF2422FDFEA9" box="[1281,1447,230,256]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="23.[136,229,1993,2015]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,190,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-17@23.[164,1423,190,1968]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 12. A–E. Sida urens. A. Flower. B. Adaxial surface of leaf. C. Branch with flowers and flowers buds. D. Schizocarp. E. Branch with mature schizocarps. F–J. Sida viarum. F. Flower. G. Adaxial surface of leaf. H. Abaxial surface of leaf. I. Branch. J. Immature schizocarps and leaves. Photographs by Martin Grings." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415513" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415513/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">Figures 12F–J</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="9FDD2A080B6B165A78DDFEC827E6FE8D" box="[136,188,266,292]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="26.[136,229,1957,1979]" captionTargetBox="[196,1391,245,1933]" captionTargetId="figure-54@26.[196,1391,245,1933]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 14. Mericarps. A. Sida anomala. B. Sida confusa. C. Sida farroupilhensis. D. Sida glaziovii. E. Sida cerradoensis. F. Sida cordifolia. G. Sida dubia. H. Sida linifolia. I. Sida lonchitis. J. Sida nemorensis. K. Sida paradoxa. L. Sida planicaulis. M. Sida potentilloides.N. Sida reitzii. O. Sida regnellii. P. Sida rhombifolia.Q. Sida riedelii. R. Sida rubifolia.S. Sida spinosa.T. Sida tuberculata. U. Sida urens. V. Sida viarum. Photographs by Martin Grings." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415519" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415519/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">14V</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4FFC65060B6B165A78E8FEEC26EAFD89" pageId="27" pageNumber="132" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="0759368D0B6B165A78E8FEEC26EAFD89" blockId="27.[136,1452,158,724]" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B6B165A78E8FEEC25B8FEE1" bold="true" box="[189,738,302,328]" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">Distribution, habitat and conservation status:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName id="C0E64D0E0B6B165A7AABFEEC24DDFEE1" box="[766,903,302,328]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="27" pageNumber="132" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="viarum">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B6B165A7AABFEEC24DDFEE1" box="[766,903,302,328]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">Sida viarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a South American species (
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B6B165A7C8AFEEC2209FEE1" box="[1247,1363,302,328]" name="Argentina" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B6B165A7D35FEEC22FDFEE1" box="[1376,1447,302,328]" name="Brazil" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B6B165A78DDFE902780FEC5" box="[136,218,338,364]" name="Bolivia" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B6B165A7942FE9126DBFEC4" box="[279,385,339,365]" name="Paraguay" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
) that reaches as far north, southern 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B6B165A7B73FE902426FEC5" box="[806,892,338,364]" name="Mexico" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6B165A7BDBFE90237CFEC5" author="Fryxell, P. A." box="[910,1062,338,364]" pageId="27" pageNumber="132" pagination="1 - 522" refId="ref18772" refString="Fryxell, P. A. (1988) Malvaceae of Mexico. Systematic Botany Monograph 25: 1 - 522. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 25027717" type="journal article" year="1988">Fryxell 1988</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6B165A7C61FE902240FEC5" author="Zuloaga, F. O. &amp; Morrone, O. &amp; Belgrano M. J." box="[1076,1306,338,364]" pageId="27" pageNumber="132" pagination="1 - 3348" refId="ref20813" refString="Zuloaga, F. O., Morrone, O. &amp; Belgrano M. J. (2008) Catalogo de las plantas vasculares del Cono Sur (Argentina, sur de Brasil, Chile, Paraguay y Uruguay). Monographs in Systematic Botany from the Missouri Botanical Garden 107: 1 - 3348." type="journal article" year="2008">
Zuloaga 
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B6B165A7CCFFE91238FFEC5" box="[1178,1237,338,364]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6B165A7D73FE9027B1FE39" author="Alverson, W. S. &amp; Michel, L. R. C. de &amp; Dorr, L. J. &amp; Fryxell, P. A. &amp; Krapovickas, A. &amp; Meneses, Q. R. I." pageId="27" pageNumber="132" pagination="786 - 819" refId="ref17710" refString="Alverson, W. S., Michel, L. R. C. de, Dorr, L. J., Fryxell, P. A., Krapovickas, A. &amp; Meneses, Q. R. I. (2014) Malvaceae. In: Jorgensen, P. M., Nee, M. H. &amp; Beck, S. G. (Eds.) Catalogo de las plantas vasculares de Bolivia, Monographs in systematic botany from the Missouri Botanical Garden. Missouri Botanical Garden Press., St. Louis, pp. 786 - 819." type="book chapter" year="2014">
Alverson 
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B6B165A7DC2FE9127FFFE39" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B6B165A794AFEB42639FE39" box="[287,355,374,400]" name="Brazil" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">Brazil</collectingCountry>
the species occurs in north, northeast, midwest, southeast and south region, but not in all states (
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6B165A78C5FE582630FE1D" author="Zuloaga, F. O. &amp; Morrone, O. &amp; Belgrano M. J." box="[144,362,410,436]" pageId="27" pageNumber="132" pagination="1 - 3348" refId="ref20813" refString="Zuloaga, F. O., Morrone, O. &amp; Belgrano M. J. (2008) Catalogo de las plantas vasculares del Cono Sur (Argentina, sur de Brasil, Chile, Paraguay y Uruguay). Monographs in Systematic Botany from the Missouri Botanical Garden 107: 1 - 3348." type="journal article" year="2008">
Zuloaga 
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B6B165A78A6FE592670FE1D" box="[243,298,410,436]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B6B165A7921FE582559FE1D" author="Bovini, M. G." box="[372,515,410,436]" pageId="27" pageNumber="132" refId="ref18092" refString="Bovini, M. G. (2020) Sida in Lista de Especies da Flora do Brasil. Jardim Botanico do Rio de Janeiro. Available from: http: // floradobrasil. jbrj. gov. br / jabot / floradobrasil / FB 9206 (accessed 7 July 2020)" type="url" year="2020">Bovini 2020</bibRefCitation>
). In Rio Grande Sul, the species is distributed in Bush grassland, Inland sub-montane grassland, Sandy grassland, Coastal grassland, and occasionally in 
<taxonomicName id="C0E64D0E0B6B165A7B22FE7C248BFE71" box="[887,977,446,472]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Aristida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="27" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Aristida</taxonomicName>
grassland (
<figureCitation id="9FDD2A080B6B165A7C04FE7C2398FE71" box="[1105,1218,446,472]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="24.[136,229,1957,1979]" captionTargetBox="[266,1345,253,1884]" captionTargetId="figure-25@24.[204,1384,190,1933]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 13. Distribution map of Sida urens and S. viarum in Rio Grande do Sul state, Brazil." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415517" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415517/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="132">Figure 13</figureCitation>
). The species is here considered Least Concern (LC) because it has a large EOO (greater than 
<quantity id="C01E9B680B6B165A7B9CFE20233DFE56" box="[969,1127,482,511]" metricMagnitude="9" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="132" unit="km" value="3000000.0">3,000,000 km</quantity>
²) and an AOO around 2,000 with the available records.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
